# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fresh-deno
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno explicitly takes on the role of both runtime and package manager within a single executable, rather than requiring a separate package-management program.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno was announced at JSConf EU 2018 by Ryan Dahl in his talk "10 Things I Regret About Node.js".
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] He eventually presented the prototype of Deno, aiming to achieve system call bindings through message passing with serialization tools such as Protocol Buffers, and to provide command line flags for access control.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno was initially written in Go and used Protocol Buffers for serialization between privileged (Go, with system call access) and unprivileged (V8) sides.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] However, Go was soon replaced with Rust due to concerns of double runtime and garbage collection pressure.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] A standard library, modeled after Go's standard library, was created in November 2018 to provide extensive tools and utilities, partially solving Node.js' dependency tree explosion problem.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] The official Deno 1.0 was released on May 13, 2020.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno Deploy, inspired by Cloudflare Workers, was released on June 23, 2021.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Announced May 4, 2022 Beta 4 improved the dashboard and added billing functionality.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno Fresh 1.0 was announced June 28, 2022.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] It features a new full stack web framework for Deno that by default sends zero JavaScript to the client.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] The framework has no build step which allows for an order of magnitude improvements in deployment times.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Version 1.1 was released September 8, 2022.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno SaaSKit beta was announced April 4, 2023.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] It is an open-source, modern SaaS template built with Fresh and Deno.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] It primarily brings Node.js compatibility improvements and removes deprecated features.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno aims to be a productive and secure scripting environment for the modern programmer.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Similar to Node.js, Deno emphasizes event-driven architecture, providing a set of non-blocking core I/O utilities, along with their blocking versions.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno could be used to create web servers, perform scientific computations, etc.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno is open source software under the MIT License.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Deno and Node.js are both runtimes built on the V8 JavaScript engine developed by the Chromium Project, the engine used for Chromium and Google Chrome web browsers.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] They both have internal event loops and provide command-line interfaces for running scripts and a wide range of system utilities.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Supports URLs for loading local or remote dependencies, similar to browsers, and uses module specifiers like `npm:` and `node:` to import NPM or polyfill Node.JS modules.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Does not require a package manager for resource fetching, thus no need for a registry like npm.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Supports TypeScript out of the box, using a snapshotted TypeScript compiler or the swc compiler with caching mechanisms.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Aims for better compatibility with browsers with a wide range of Web APIs.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Restricts file system and network access by default in order to run sandboxed code.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Supports a single API to utilize promises, ES6 and TypeScript features whereas Node.js supports both promise and callback APIs.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Minimizes core API size, while providing a large standard library with no external dependencies.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] Uses message passing channels for invoking privileged system APIs and using bindings.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] On March 29, 2021, Deno Land Inc was announced, with backing in millions of dollars from Shasta Ventures, Mozilla Corporation and a few others.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] It was established to further the development of Deno and provide a commercial offering to users.
[src:fresh-deno/deno-software] A year on, Deno announced a further $21 million in Series A funding led by Sequoia Capital.
[src:fresh-deno/hydration-web-development] Frameworks that use hydration include Next.js and Nuxt.
[src:fresh-deno/hydration-web-development] React v16.0 introduced a "hydrate" function, which hydrates an element, in its API.
[src:fresh-deno/hydration-web-development] In *progressive rehydration*, individual pieces of a server-rendered application are “booted up” over time, rather than the current common approach of initializing the entire application at once.
[src:fresh-deno/hydration-web-development] This can help reduce the amount of JavaScript required to make pages interactive, since client-side upgrading of low priority parts of the page can be deferred to prevent blocking the main thread.
[src:fresh-deno/hydration-web-development] One framework that supports partial rehydration is Elder.js, which is based on Svelte.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Fresh is a small, fast and extensible full stack web framework built on Web Standards.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] It’s designed for building high-quality, performant, and personalized web applications.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] The core idea powering Fresh is to render server generated HTML pages and only ship JavaScript for areas in the page that need to be interactive.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] This is often referred to as the Island Architecture.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Fresh is ideal for sites and apps that are primarily server rendered, like a home page, an e-commerce shop or something like GitHub or Bluesky.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Fresh’s small API surface and file-based conventions also make it a great fit for AI-assisted development.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Agents can scaffold routes, add middleware, and build features with minimal context because the framework is simple and predictable.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] That said, if you want to build a Single-Page-App (=SPA), then Fresh is not the right framework.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Fresh powers deno.com and Deno Deploy among many other projects at Deno.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] It’s also used by deco.cx for e-commerce projects.
[src:fresh-deno/introduction] Deploy with a single click on Deno Deploy, or package your app in a Docker container for any cloud provider or self-hosted infrastructure.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:fresh-deno/server-side-scripting] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:fresh-deno/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:fresh-deno/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
